{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657921"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:38:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:38:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20687"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20687"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.15,0.65,0.1,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13563"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96169"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13563"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20687"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78897"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11657"},{"type":"tags","id":"12456"},{"type":"tags","id":"12565"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32520"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32522"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96169"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a mechanism by which obesity increases cancer risk?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduced estrogen synthesis from androgen precursors","Enhanced adiponectin secretion from adipose tissue","Elevated free insulin-like growth factor 1 levels","Increased production of sex hormone-binding globulin","Decreased activation of oncogenic RAS and PI3K/AKT pathways"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eelevated free insulin-like growth factor 1 levels\u003C/strong\u003E. Obesity leads to insulin resistance and hyperinsulinemia, which increases levels of free insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1). IGF-1 is a potent mitogen, and its receptor (IGFR-1) is highly expressed in many human cancers. When activated, IGFR-1 stimulates the RAS and PI3K/AKT signaling pathways, which promote cellular proliferation and survival in both normal and neoplastic cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased activation of oncogenic RAS and PI3K/AKT pathways\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because obesity actually increases activation of these pathways through elevated IGF-1 levels, promoting cancer development.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased production of sex hormone-binding globulin\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because obesity inhibits the production of sex hormone-binding globulin (SHBG) in the liver, which increases the bioavailability of estrogen and contributes to hormone-dependent cancers.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced adiponectin secretion from adipose tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because adiponectin secretion is reduced in obesity, not enhanced. Adiponectin has anti-neoplastic properties, including promotion of p53 and p21 activity, which are compromised in obese individuals.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced estrogen synthesis from androgen precursors\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect because obesity actually increases the synthesis of estrogen from androgen precursors, particularly in adipose tissue, which contributes to the development of hormone-sensitive cancers.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EObesity is associated with approximately 40% of all cancers in the United States, with a slightly higher prevalence in women than men. The mechanisms linking obesity to cancer are multifactorial, including altered insulin and IGF-1 signaling, changes in sex hormone metabolism, reduced adiponectin-mediated tumor suppression, and chronic inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Obesity is associated with approximately 40% of all cancers in the United States, with a higher prevalence in women than men.","Hyperinsulinemia in obesity increases free insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1) levels, which activates growth-promoting pathways like RAS and PI3K/AKT.","Obesity alters steroid hormone metabolism, increasing estrogen synthesis and bioavailability by reducing sex hormone-binding globulin.","Reduced adiponectin secretion in obesity compromises its anti-neoplastic effects, including p53 and p21-mediated tumor suppression."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 9; page 448-449."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78897"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20687"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78897"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-31T15:00:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-31T15:01:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13563"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96169"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api